Rhyme and cohort competitors in word recognition â€“ a replication of Allopenna et al (1998)

This study is a replication of Allopenna et al (1998) using a 2AFC (instead of a 4AFC) paradigm. Thanks to Liz Simmons and Jim Magnuson for providing the visual and auditory stimuli.

The main research question is: In a web-based eye-tracking paradigm using webgazer.js, can we replicate standard onset competitor and rhyme competitor effects?

Answer: The analysis below suggests that onset competitor effects replicate very clearly and rhyme competitor effects do so less clearly. The relatively weaker rhyme competitor effects may be due to the relatively noisier web-based eye-tracking data â€“ rhyme competitor effects are generally weaker than onset competitor effects and consequently more difficult to detect.

Hereâ€™s the experiment weâ€™re analyzing.

Participants: 57 students from Judith Degenâ€™s LING 145 â€œIntroduction to Psycholinguisticsâ€ class, Autumn 2020, and their friends

Materials:

  1. There were 3 conditions, with 9 items in each:
  • Cohort: target word shared onset with competitor word (eg, â€œbubblesâ€ and â€œbunnyâ€).
  • Rhyme: target word rhymed with competitor word (eg, â€œpocketâ€ and â€œrocketâ€)
  • Unrelated: control condition where target word had no overlap with competitor word (eg, â€œdoctorâ€ and â€œmuffinâ€)
  1. The stimuli were split into 4 lists, with 27 items each (target position was counterbalanced within and across lists; each word was the target on one list and the competitor on the other).

Procedure:

  1. Subjects listened to instructions like â€œFind the bubblesâ€ in a web-based 2AFC visual world paradigm.
  2. Subjects clicked on the target object after each instruction to advance to the next trial.

Results:

Preprocessing

  • Trials with wrong selections were removed. 4 cases

Analysis

  • computed regions of interest: target, competitor, center, other
  • aligned time relative to target word onset and binned samples into 60ms bins
  • plotted proportions of looks over time (all regions vs just target and competitor)
  • additional analyses?
# load data
d = read.csv('../data/main2-cohort-merged.csv') %>% 
  select(-proliferate.condition,-audio_loaded_time,-criticality,-error) %>% 
  mutate(trial = tolower(trial),selected_img = tolower(selected_img), img_left = tolower(img_left), img_right = tolower(img_right)) %>% 
  separate(trial,c("target_item","target_type")) %>% 
  mutate(target_item=fct_recode(target_item, cookie = "cookies")) %>% 
  separate(selected_img,c(NA,NA,"selected_item","selected_type",NA)) %>% 
  separate(img_right,c(NA,NA,"right_item",NA,NA)) %>% 
  separate(img_left,c(NA,NA,"left_item",NA,NA)) %>% 
  mutate(target_location = case_when(left_item == target_item ~ "left",
                                     right_item == target_item ~ "right",
                                     TRUE ~ "no target/error")) %>% 
  left_join(audio_info,by=c("target_item"))
